1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 7. Qb3 O-O 8.
Be2 Nbd7 9. Bf3 Nb6 10. Nge2 Bg4 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 12. a4 Nf6 13. Nf4 Qd7 14. a5 $1
{Now White is going to keep his extra pawn. You may think: "But this extra
pawn is doubled". That's true, but this doubled pawn also controls important
central squares. After you keep your material, your plan should be to use the
strong e5 square with a knight. If Black takes it, recapture with the "e" pawn;
if Black plays f6 at some stage, then White can use the e6 square; and in case
Black lets the knight appear on e5, this piece will create strong pressure on
Black's position.} Nc8 15. O-O Nd6 16. Rd1 (16. Nd3 {Going directly to the
plan was a better option.}) 16... Rac8 17. Nd3 $1 {Now White understands what
the plan is!} Nfe4 18. Be3 {Finishing opening tasks before starting an attack.}
(18. Ne5 Qf5 {And Black has some counterplay. White should select the most
accurate moment to realise his plan.}) 18... Nxc3 19. bxc3 Qb5 20. Ra3 {
Keeping the tension. Now White has slight advantage and a clear plan.} Rc4 $6 {
Helps White implement his plan with tempo.} 21. Ne5 {Of course. Also 21.Rb1
was an interesting alternative.} (21. Rb1 Qxb3 (21... Qxd5 22. Nb2 Qe4 23. Nxc4
Nxc4 24. Raa1 $16) 22. Rbxb3 $16) 21... Rc7 22. c4 Qxb3 23. Rxb3 {Now in this
endgame White has the advantage.} f6 24. c5 fxe5 25. cxd6 exd6 26. dxe5 Bxe5
27. Bxa7 Ra8 28. Bb6 Rc2 29. g3 Rac8 30. Be3 R8c7 31. Kg2 Ra2 32. Rb5 h5 33.
Rdb1 Ra4 34. Kh3 Ra2 35. Kg2 Ra4 36. h3 Rf7 37. Rc1 Bd4 38. Bxd4 Rxd4 39. Rc3
Kg7 40. Rf3 Ra4 {What we should learn from this game: 1. How to play in the
positions where Black allows White to maintain the extra pawn. 2. We should
first develop and just then start an attack. We should know this already, but
it is never bad to review.} 1-0

